{{Infobox SCOTUS case |Litigants=Federal Election Commission v. Massachusetts Citizens for Life, Inc. |ArgueDate=Oct 7 |ArgueYear=1986 |DecideDate=Dec 15 |DecideYear=1986 |FullName=Federal Election Commission v. Massachusetts Citizens for Life, Inc. |Docket=85-701 |USVol=479 |USPage=238 |ParallelCitations=107 S. Ct. 616; 93 [[L. Ed. 2d]] 539; 1986 [[U.S. LEXIS]] 26 |Prior= |Subsequent= |Holding= Massachusetts Citizens for Life violated the Federal Election Campaign Act by distributing flyers asking voters to vote “for life” paid for with treasury funds, however that section of FECA itself violated the First Amendment. |SCOTUS= |Majority= Brennan |JoinMajority= Marshall, Powell, Scalia |Concurrence=O’Connor |Dissent= Rehnquist |JoinDissent=White, Blackmun, Stevens |LawsApplied=[[First Amendment to the United States Constitution|U.S. Const. amend. I]] }}
In '''''Federal Election Commission v. Massachusetts Citizens for Life, Inc.''''', 479 U.S. 238 (1986), the [[U.S. Supreme Court]] ruled that Massachusetts Citizens for Life, Inc. violated the [[Federal Election Campaign Act]] by distributing flyers asking voters to vote “for life” paid for with treasury funds. However, the court also ruled that the FECA section that required any spending by corporations on political campaigning to be done through [[political action committee]]s (PACs) was itself a violation of the [[First Amendment]] rights of nonprofit political and ideological groups.<ref>{{Cite news | last = Wermiel | first = Stephen | title = High Court Overturns Law Requiring Nonprofit Political Groups to Use PACs | newspaper = Wall Street Journal, Eastern edition | pages = 4 | date =16 Dec 1986 | via = ProQuest |url=https://search.proquest.com/docview/397987118/ |url-access=subscription | access-date = 2017-05-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.oyez.org/cases/1986/85-701|title=Federal Election Commission v. Massachusetts Citizens for Life, Inc.|publisher= Oyez| access-date = 2017-05-16}}</ref>
